div.p:
Walter’s name presumably refers to Mileto, Calabria, which is called Melide in the chronicle of Roger of Hoveden. Norman connections encouraged frequent contact between England and Sicily at this time. Roger records that Richard I stayed at the town’s Benedictine abbey of the Holy Trinity on 21 September 1190;
William Stubbs, ed., Chronica magistri Rogeri de Houedene, Rerum Britannicarum medii aevi scriptores 51 (London: Longmans, Green, Reader, and Dyer, 1868–1871), 3:45; Henry T. Riley, trans., The Annals of Roger de Hoveden (London: Bohn, 1853), 2:157. this abbey was established by Roger I, the Norman count of Sicily, also responsible for an Augustinian foundation at Bagnara.
Giuseppe Occhiato, ‘L’abbatiale détruite de la Sainte-Trinité de Mileto (Calabre)’, Cahiers de civilisation médiévale 21, no. 83 (1978): 231–52, https://doi.org/10/gftnj2; G. A. Loud, The Latin Church in Norman Italy (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2007), 88–89, 276, https://doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511721083. One can find a Peter de Melide living in England a few decades before Walter.
Melville Madison Bigelow, Placita Anglo-Normannica: Law Cases from William I to Richard I (Boston: Little, Brown, 1879), 312–13, https://archive.org/details/placitaanglonorm00bige. Peter of Blois embarked on an ultimately disastrous venture in the Norman government;
Karla Mallette, The Kingdom of Sicily, 1100-1250: A Literary History, The Middle Ages Series (Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 2005), 94. Robert of Cricklade also journeyed there.
James Craigie Robertson, ed., ‘Miracula sancti Thomæ Cantuariensis, auctore Benedicto, abbate Petriburgensi’, in Materials for the History of Thomas Becket, Archbishop of Canterbury, vol. 2, Rerum Britannicarum medii aevi scriptores 67 (London: Longman, 1875), 97, https://archive.org/details/materialsforhist02robe. Walter may himself have been a Norman.
